HIGH PRIORITY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[H-1] No integration tests for graph engine execution paths
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The DAG executor (src/graph/dag_executor.rs) is the most complex subsystem in
  Renderflow.  It has doc-tests for the MultiTargetDag struct, but no integration
  tests covering the DagExecutor's wave-parallel execution, incremental caching
  behaviour, or error propagation through the graph.

Rationale:
  Regressions in the graph executor would silently corrupt multi-target builds
  or silently skip outputs.  The absence of integration tests means these failure
  modes would only surface at runtime.

Recommended fix:
  Add tests/graph_executor_test.rs covering:
  • Single-edge single-target execution
  • Multi-target DAG with shared intermediate node (verify step runs once)
  • Parallel wave execution (verify all targets are reached)
  • Cache hit: unchanged input node skips downstream execution
  • Error propagation: transform failure returns an error and halts the wave

Effort: 3–4 hours

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[H-2] AiTransform API key stored in YAML config in plaintext
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  AiTransform supports an optional `api_key` field.  When configured via YAML
  (src/transforms/yaml_loader.rs), this key is deserialized directly from the
  config file, meaning users must store the API key in their renderflow.yaml.
  There is no support for environment variable substitution or secret store
  integration.

Rationale:
  Storing secrets in config files risks accidental commits and exposure in logs.
  Users rendering documents in CI pipelines will have no secure way to supply
  the key.

Recommended fix:
  1. Add `api_key_env` field to the AI transform config: read the key from the
     named environment variable at runtime instead of from the YAML value.
  2. Log a warning (not the value) if the key is provided inline in YAML and
     the environment is a CI context (CI=true).
  3. Document the `api_key_env` pattern in the README and in CONTRIBUTING.md.

Effort: 2–3 hours

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[H-3] Snap package build untested in CI
─────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The release pipeline builds a Snap package via snapcore/action-build@v1.
  The CI workflow (ci.yml) does not validate the snapcraft.yaml file or perform
  a test build.  The first time the Snap build runs is during a real release,
  where failures block all artifact uploads.

Rationale:
  A snapcraft.yaml syntax error or missing field discovered only during release
  will delay the entire release pipeline and require a re-run after hotfixing.

Recommended fix:
  Add a `validate-snap` job to ci.yml that runs `snap pack --check-skeleton`
  or snapcraft's lint command on snap/snapcraft.yaml to catch structural errors
  early.

Effort: 1 hour

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
MEDIUM PRIORITY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-1] TransformRegistry failure mode `Abort` is under-documented
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  src/transforms/registry.rs exposes a `FailureMode` enum with `Abort` and
  `Skip` variants, but the registry-level documentation does not describe the
  implications of each mode on downstream transforms or the output pipeline.
  The YAML loader (yaml_loader.rs) maps `on_failure: abort|skip` but this is
  not mentioned in the README or any user-facing documentation.

Rationale:
  Users composing multi-step transform chains need to understand whether a
  failed optional transform (e.g. an AI step that times out) aborts the entire
  build or is gracefully skipped.

Recommended fix:
  Add a "Transform failure modes" section to the README under the Transforms
  heading.  Include YAML examples for both `abort` and `skip`.

Effort: 1 hour

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-2] `cargo update --workspace` in bump-version may produce non-reproducible lock file
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  bump-version.yml runs `cargo update --workspace` after editing Cargo.toml.
  This updates ALL transitive dependencies to their latest semver-compatible
  versions, not just the version-bumped package.  The resulting Cargo.lock may
  differ non-trivially from what was tested in CI.

Rationale:
  If a transitive dependency released a buggy patch between the last CI run and
  the bump, the release binary will silently include that regression.

Recommended fix:
  Replace `cargo update --workspace` with `cargo update --precise <new-version>
  renderflow` to update only the crate's own entry in Cargo.lock without pulling
  in unrelated dependency upgrades.

Effort: 30 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-3] Manifest update in release pipeline is not atomic — concurrent pushes may conflict
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The update-homebrew-formula, update-scoop-manifest, and update-aur-pkgbuild
  jobs each fetch main, apply a change, and push — sequentially.  If another
  push lands on main between fetches (e.g. a hotfix), the push will fail with
  a non-fast-forward error and the release manifest will not be updated.

Rationale:
  Manifest update failures leave package manager users on an older version even
  though a GitHub Release exists.  The sequential pipeline means a single failure
  blocks all subsequent manifest jobs.

Recommended fix:
  Add `git pull --rebase origin main` before each manifest commit-and-push step,
  and add `continue-on-error: true` with a follow-up notification step so the
  failure is visible without blocking the release.

Effort: 1 hour

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-4] `ureq` used for AI HTTP calls but not in dev-dependencies — no mocking
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  AiTransform makes live HTTP calls to Ollama / OpenAI via `ureq`.  There are
  no tests for AiTransform because the calls require a live backend.  The
  `ureq` crate does not have a built-in mock facility.

Rationale:
  The AI transform is untested.  Any regression in the request construction,
  response parsing, or cache invalidation logic will only surface in production.

Recommended fix:
  1. Extract the HTTP call into an injectable `AiClient` trait.
  2. Provide a `MockAiClient` in test code that returns canned responses.
  3. Add unit tests for: successful response, cache hit, cache miss, error
     response (non-200), and malformed JSON.

Effort: 4 hours

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-5] Audio and image format support not validated in CI
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The CI build-and-test job runs on ubuntu-latest which does not have FFmpeg
  installed.  Tests that exercise audio or image conversion strategies are
  therefore either absent or gated by tool availability checks.  The
  AudioStrategy and ImageStrategy code paths are never exercised in CI.

Rationale:
  A logic error in FfmpegAudioArgs or FfmpegImageArgs will only be caught when
  a user runs renderflow with an audio or image output configured.

Recommended fix:
  Add `sudo apt-get install -y ffmpeg` to the CI job's setup steps, and add a
  basic integration test that exercises at least one audio→audio and one
  image→image conversion using a small test fixture.

Effort: 2–3 hours

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[M-6] `clippy` only runs with `-D warnings` on the CI branch — not on release builds
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  ci.yml runs `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`, but the release pipeline does not
  run clippy at all.  Clippy warnings that are suppressed in development may
  still appear and cause confusion when reviewing release artifacts.

Rationale:
  Minor issue, but consistent lint enforcement improves code quality and avoids
  flag-day accumulation of warnings.

Recommended fix:
  Add a clippy step to the generate-changelog job, or add a dedicated lint gate
  job to the release workflow that must pass before build-binaries starts.

Effort: 30 minutes

