LOW PRIORITY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-1] `#[allow(dead_code)]` in aggregation module suppresses useful warnings
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  src/transforms/aggregation.rs carries `#![allow(dead_code)]` at the top of
  the file with the comment "not yet called from the main binary entry-point".
  This suppresses warnings for the entire module unconditionally.

Rationale:
  Dead-code warnings exist to flag unused public API and accidental orphaning
  of logic.  Suppressing them globally on a module hides future regressions.

Recommended fix:
  Instead of a module-level allow, annotate only the specific items that are
  intentionally unused with `#[allow(dead_code)]`, or better, expose them via
  integration test usage so the compiler's liveness analysis covers them.

Effort: 30 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-2] `Cargo.toml` excludes `dist/` but dist/ may contain stale artifacts
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The `dist/` directory is excluded from `cargo package` but is present in the
  repository.  It is not listed in `.gitignore`, meaning rendered output files
  can be accidentally committed.

Rationale:
  Committed build artifacts inflate repository size and create confusing diffs.

Recommended fix:
  Add `dist/` to `.gitignore`.  Verify the `.gitignore` also covers
  `.renderflow-cache.json` and `.renderflow-deps.json` (the incremental build
  state files), which should never be committed.

Effort: 15 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-3] Release verification job does not check .deb, .rpm, or .snap assets
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The verify-release job in release.yml checks for the 20 binary/checksum
  assets but does not verify that .deb, .rpm, .snap, and .nupkg packages were
  uploaded successfully.

Rationale:
  If a packaging job silently uploads zero files (e.g. glob expansion fails),
  the verify step will pass without detecting the missing packages.

Recommended fix:
  Extend the EXPECTED array in verify-release to include at least one file
  pattern for each package type (.deb, .rpm, .snap, .nupkg).

Effort: 30 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-4] CONTRIBUTING.md references `cargo-release` in the release config table
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  CONTRIBUTING.md lists release.toml as "`cargo-release` settings", but the
  actual release pipeline does not use cargo-release — it uses a custom
  bump-version.yml workflow.  The release.toml is present but unused.

Rationale:
  Misleading documentation causes contributor confusion about the release
  process.

Recommended fix:
  Remove or clarify the release.toml entry in CONTRIBUTING.md's release
  configuration table.  If release.toml is genuinely unused, remove the file
  or add a comment explaining its status.

Effort: 15 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-5] The `examples/` directory is not validated in CI
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  The `examples/` directory contains working render configs (hello-world,
  transforms).  There is no CI job that runs `renderflow build` against these
  examples to verify they still work after changes to the core engine.

Rationale:
  Breaking changes to config field names or output types will not be caught
  until a user attempts to use the example.

Recommended fix:
  Add a `validate-examples` CI job that installs renderflow from the built
  binary and runs `renderflow build --config examples/hello-world/renderflow.yaml
  --dry-run`.  Dry-run mode does not require Pandoc/Tectonic/FFmpeg to be
  installed.

Effort: 1 hour

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-6] `renderflow.code-workspace` committed to main branch
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  renderflow.code-workspace is a VS Code workspace file that records per-user
  editor settings.  It is committed to the repository and not listed in
  .gitignore.  It is excluded from `cargo package` but is part of the public
  repository.

Rationale:
  Editor config files don't belong in shared repositories unless they encode
  project-level settings useful to all contributors (e.g. recommended
  extensions).  Committing it can cause spurious diffs when different developers
  open the workspace.

Recommended fix:
  Move it to `.gitignore` or to a `.vscode/` directory and document recommended
  extensions there instead.

Effort: 15 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-7] Missing MSRV badge in README
────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  Cargo.toml specifies `rust-version = "1.94"` (MSRV), but the README has no
  MSRV badge indicating the minimum supported Rust version.

Rationale:
  Users building from source need to know which Rust version is required.
  Without a badge, they may encounter opaque compile errors.

Recommended fix:
  Add `[![Rust MSRV](https://img.shields.io/badge/MSRV-1.94-orange)](Cargo.toml)`
  to the README badge row.

Effort: 5 minutes

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

[L-8] `ureq` v2 is pinned — v3 released with breaking changes
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Description:
  Cargo.toml pins `ureq = { version = "2", features = ["json"] }`.  ureq v3
  is available and includes significant API improvements, but upgrading is
  a breaking change that requires updating call sites in src/transforms/ai.rs.

Rationale:
  Staying on ureq v2 is not immediately harmful, but v2 will receive fewer
  security updates over time as the ecosystem migrates.

Recommended fix:
  Evaluate ureq v3 migration.  The changes primarily affect the builder API
  for request construction.  Update src/transforms/ai.rs accordingly and bump
  the dependency in Cargo.toml.

Effort: 2 hours

